        "content": "<p><strong>Complete Meal Components:</strong> Main + 2 Sides + Rice</p>\n<p><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Medium | <strong>Servings:</strong> 4 servings</p>\n<h3>Time Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Total Prep Time:</strong> 25 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Marination Time:</strong> 30 minutes vacuum (vs 4-8 hours traditional)</li>\n  <li><strong>Cook Time:</strong> 10-12 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Total Time:</strong> 70 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Storage Duration:</strong> Marinated salmon: 6-12 months frozen</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why This Meal is Special</h3>\n<h4>Thick Paste Penetration:</h4>\n<p>Miso paste is thick and viscous. Traditionally, it sits on the surface of fish, requiring hours to slowly seep in. Vacuum sealing forces this dense paste into the delicate flakes of the salmon instantly. The result is a fillet that is seasoned through and through, not just on top.</p>\n<p>The vacuum environment also prevents the delicate omega-3 fats in salmon from oxidizing, keeping the fish tasting fresh-caught even after months in the freezer.</p>\n<h3>COMPONENT 1: Vacuum-Infused Miso Salmon</h3>\n<h4>Ingredients:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>4 salmon fillets (approx 150-180g / 5-6 oz each), skin on or off</li>\n  <li>60g ( cup) white miso paste</li>\n  <li>30ml (2 tbsp) mirin</li>\n  <li>15ml (1 tbsp) soy sauce</li>\n  <li>15ml (1 tbsp) sake or rice vinegar</li>\n  <li>15g (1 tbsp) sugar</li>\n  <li>10g (2 tsp) fresh ginger, grated</li>\n  <li>1 tsp sesame oil</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Equipment:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer + bags</li>\n  <li>Small bowl</li>\n  <li>Whisk</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Instructions:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Make Marinade:</strong> Whisk miso, mirin, soy sauce, sake, sugar, ginger, and sesame oil until smooth.</li>\n  <li><strong>Coat:</strong> Pat salmon dry. Brush marinade generously over all sides of fillets.</li>\n  <li><strong>Vacuum Seal:</strong> Place fillets in bag (single layer).</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>CRITICAL:</strong> Use <strong>Pulse</strong> mode. Miso is thick but can still be sucked into sealer.</li>\n  <li>Seal gently.</li>\n</ul>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Marinate:</strong> Let sit 30 minutes at room temp or freeze immediately.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Cooking:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Thaw:</strong> In fridge overnight.</li>\n  <li><strong>Broil:</strong> Place on foil-lined sheet. Broil on High for 6-8 minutes, watching carefully for caramelization.</li>\n  <li><strong>Pan Sear:</strong> Medium heat, 3-4 mins per side.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Storage:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Freezer: 6-12 months</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>COMPONENT 2: Teriyaki-Marinated Bok Choy</h3>\n<h4>Ingredients:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>4 heads baby bok choy, halved lengthwise</li>\n  <li>60ml ( cup) teriyaki sauce (store-bought or homemade)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp sesame oil</li>\n  <li>1 clove garlic, minced</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Instructions:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Wash:</strong> Rinse bok choy thoroughly between leaves. Dry well.</li>\n  <li><strong>Marinate:</strong> Toss with teriyaki, sesame oil, garlic.</li>\n  <li><strong>Vacuum Seal:</strong> Place in bag. Pulse seal (liquid).</li>\n  <li><strong>Marinate:</strong> 15-20 minutes room temp.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Cooking:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Grill/Pan:</strong> Sear cut-side down for 2-3 minutes until charred. Flip, cook 1 min.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Storage:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Freezer: 8-10 months (texture softens, best for stir-fry if frozen)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>COMPONENT 3: Sesame Edamame</h3>\n<h4>Ingredients:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>300g (10 oz) frozen edamame (in pods or shelled)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp sesame oil</li>\n  <li>1 tsp sea salt</li>\n  <li> tsp chili flakes</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Instructions:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Season:</strong> Toss frozen edamame with oil, salt, chili.</li>\n  <li><strong>Vacuum Seal:</strong> Seal in bag.</li>\n  <li><strong>Store:</strong> Keep frozen until ready.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Cooking:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Steam:</strong> Microwave in vented bag 2-3 minutes. Or boil 3 mins.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>COMPONENT 4: Sticky Rice Portions</h3>\n<h4>Ingredients:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>2 cups sushi rice or short-grain rice</li>\n  <li>2.5 cups water</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Instructions:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Cook:</strong> Rinse rice until clear. Cook in rice cooker/pot.</li>\n  <li><strong>Cool:</strong> Spread to cool completely.</li>\n  <li><strong>Seal:</strong> Portion into 4 bags. Flatten. Seal.</li>\n  <li><strong>Store:</strong> Freeze flat.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Reheating:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Microwave vented bag 2 mins.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>COMPLETE MEAL ASSEMBLY</h3>\n<h4>Timing:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>5:30 PM: Thaw salmon/bok choy (if frozen)</li>\n  <li>5:45 PM: Preheat broiler</li>\n  <li>5:50 PM: Reheat rice and edamame</li>\n  <li>5:55 PM: Broil salmon and sear bok choy</li>\n  <li>6:05 PM: Plate</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Plating:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Bed of sticky rice</li>\n  <li>Salmon on top</li>\n  <li>Bok choy on side</li>\n  <li>Sprinkle edamame around</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Nutrition:</strong> ~550 calories, 35g protein, 20g fat, 55g carbs</p>\n"
