        "content": "<p><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Medium | <strong>Servings:</strong> 6-8 servings (approx 30-40 meatballs)</p>\n<h3>Time Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Prep Time:</strong> 30 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Marination Time:</strong> N/A</li>\n  <li><strong>Cook Time:</strong> N/A (Freezing raw)</li>\n  <li><strong>Total Time:</strong> 30 minutes active</li>\n  <li><strong>Storage Duration:</strong> 2-3 years frozen</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>1 kg (2.2 lbs) ground beef</li>\n  <li>500g (1.1 lbs) ground pork (adds fat and flavor)</li>\n  <li>100g (1 cup) breadcrumbs</li>\n  <li>100g (1 cup) parmesan cheese, grated</li>\n  <li>2 large eggs</li>\n  <li>60ml (Â¼ cup) milk</li>\n  <li>30g (Â½ cup) fresh parsley, chopped</li>\n  <li>15g (1 tbsp) dried oregano</li>\n  <li>4 cloves garlic, minced</li>\n  <li>15g (1 tbsp) salt</li>\n  <li>5g (1 tsp) black pepper</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Optional Additions:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>1 tsp fennel seeds (crushed)</li>\n  <li>Pinch of red pepper flakes</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Equipment Needed</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer</li>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer bags</li>\n  <li>Large mixing bowl</li>\n  <li>Baking sheet (for flash freezing)</li>\n  <li>Parchment paper</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Step-by-Step Instructions</h3>\n<h4>PREPARATION:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Prepare Panade:</strong> In a small bowl, mix breadcrumbs and milk. Let sit for 5 minutes to absorb. This keeps meatballs moist.</li>\n  <li><strong>Mix Ingredients:</strong> In a very large bowl, combine beef, pork, soaked breadcrumbs, parmesan, eggs, parsley, oregano, garlic, salt, and pepper.</li>\n  <li><strong>Combine:</strong> Mix gently with hands until just combined. <strong>Do not overmix</strong> or meatballs will be tough.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>VACUUM SEALING:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Shape:</strong> Form into golf-ball sized meatballs (approx 1.5 inch).</li>\n  <li><strong>Flash Freeze:</strong> Place meatballs on a parchment-lined baking sheet, not touching. Freeze for 1-2 hours until solid. This prevents them from being crushed by the vacuum.</li>\n  <li><strong>Bagging:</strong> Transfer frozen meatballs into vacuum bags. You can pack them tightly now that they are hard.</li>\n  <li><strong>Sealing:</strong> Vacuum and seal normally. Since they are frozen solids, you don't need to worry about crushing or liquids.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>STORAGE:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Store in freezer.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>COOKING FROM FROZEN/THAWED:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Cooking:</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Sauce Method:</strong> Drop frozen meatballs directly into simmering marinara sauce. Cook 20-25 mins.</li>\n  <li><strong>Oven Method:</strong> Bake frozen meatballs at 400Â°F (200Â°C) for 20-25 mins.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Storage Instructions</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Freezer:</strong> 2-3 years</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerator:</strong> 24 hours (if thawed raw)</li>\n  <li><strong>After Opening:</strong> Cook immediately</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Pro Tips (Vacuum Sealing Advantages)</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Shape Retention:</strong> Flash freezing + vacuum sealing keeps them perfectly round.</li>\n  <li><strong>Freshness:</strong> No freezer burn means they taste fresh-made even after a year.</li>\n  <li><strong>Convenience:</strong> Grab exactly as many as you need for a sub, pasta, or soup.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Variations</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Gluten-Free:</strong> Use GF breadcrumbs or almond flour.</li>\n  <li><strong>Spicy Italian:</strong> Increase red pepper flakes and garlic.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Nutrition Information (Per Serving - 4 meatballs)</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>Calories: ~380</li>\n  <li>Protein: ~28g</li>\n  <li>Fat: ~26g</li>\n  <li>Carbs: ~8g</li>\n</ul>\n"
