        "content": "<p><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Medium</p>\n<p><strong>Servings:</strong> 4-6</p>\n<h3>Time Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Prep Time:</strong> 20 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Marination Time:</strong> 30 minutes (vacuum) or 4 hours (traditional)</li>\n  <li><strong>Cook Time:</strong> 25-30 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Total Time:</strong> 55 minutes (with vacuum marination)</li>\n  <li><strong>Storage Duration:</strong> Frozen 12-18 months, Refrigerated marinated 3-4 days</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why This Meal is Special</h3>\n<p>Vacuum sealing forces the herb marinade deep into the lean tenderloin while the bacon wrapping creates a protective fat layer during freezing. The result is incredibly juicy meat with zero freezer burn, even after a year of storage. The vacuum process also allows you to pre-wrap with bacon and freeze, making this a grab-and-cook meal.</p>\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\n<h4>For the Tenderloin:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>2 pork tenderloins (800g / 1.75 lbs total)</li>\n  <li>12-16 strips streaky bacon (400g / 14 oz)</li>\n  <li>3 tbsp Dijon mustard (45ml)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp olive oil (30ml)</li>\n  <li>4 cloves garlic, minced (20g / 0.7 oz)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp fresh rosemary, chopped (10g / 0.35 oz)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp fresh thyme, chopped (5g / 0.2 oz)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp black pepper (5g)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp salt (5g)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Optional Glaze:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>2 tbsp honey (30ml)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp balsamic vinegar (15ml)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Equipment</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer</li>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer bags (gallon size)</li>\n  <li>Roasting pan or baking sheet</li>\n  <li>Meat thermometer</li>\n  <li>Kitchen twine (optional)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Instructions</h3>\n<h4>Preparation:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Pat pork tenderloins completely dry with paper towels. Remove any silver skin with a sharp knife.</li>\n  <li>In a small bowl, combine Dijon mustard, olive oil, minced garlic, rosemary, thyme, black pepper, and salt to create a paste.</li>\n  <li>Rub the herb paste evenly over all sides of both tenderloins, ensuring full coverage.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Vacuum Marination:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Place one tenderloin into a vacuum sealer bag. Seal on <strong>gentle/delicate setting</strong> (pulse mode if available) to avoid crushing the meat.</li>\n  <li>Repeat with second tenderloin.</li>\n  <li>Refrigerate for 30 minutes minimum. The vacuum pressure will force the herbs and garlic deep into the meat fibers.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Bacon Wrapping:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Remove tenderloins from bags (save marinade). Pat surface slightly dry.</li>\n  <li>Lay 6-8 bacon strips overlapping on a cutting board.</li>\n  <li>Place tenderloin at one end and roll tightly, wrapping bacon around the meat. The bacon should overlap and cover the entire surface.</li>\n  <li>Optional: Secure with kitchen twine at 2-inch intervals.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>For Immediate Cooking:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Preheat oven to 200Â°C (400Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Place bacon-wrapped tenderloins seam-side down on a roasting pan.</li>\n  <li>Optional: Brush with honey-balsamic glaze.</li>\n  <li>Roast for 25-30 minutes until internal temperature reaches 63Â°C (145Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Rest for 5 minutes, then slice into medallions.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>For Freezing:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Place each bacon-wrapped tenderloin into a fresh vacuum sealer bag.</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal on <strong>gentle setting</strong>.</li>\n  <li>Freeze flat for optimal storage and quick thawing.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Cooking from Frozen:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Thaw in refrigerator for 12-24 hours.</li>\n  <li>Follow roasting instructions above, adding 5 minutes to cook time if still slightly frozen.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Storage</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (vacuum sealed):</strong> 12-18 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (marinated, unwrapped):</strong> 3-4 days</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (cooked):</strong> 4-5 days</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Pro Tips</h3>\n<h4>Vacuum Advantage:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>The vacuum forces garlic and herbs INTO the meat, not just on the surface. You'll taste rosemary in every bite, not just the crust.</li>\n  <li>Bacon fat prevents freezer burn by creating an airtight seal around the lean tenderloin.</li>\n  <li>Pre-wrapping with bacon saves 15 minutes on busy weeknightsâ€”just thaw and roast.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Cooking Tips:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Don't overcook! Pork is safe at 63Â°C (145Â°F) with a slight pink center. Overcooking makes it dry.</li>\n  <li>Place bacon seam-side down first so it crisps and seals itself shut.</li>\n  <li>For extra crispy bacon, broil for 2 minutes at the end.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Variations:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Apple-Sage Version:</strong> Replace rosemary with fresh sage and brush with apple cider reduction.</li>\n  <li><strong>Spicy Version:</strong> Add 1 tsp chipotle powder to the herb paste.</li>\n  <li><strong>Prosciutto Wrap:</strong> Use prosciutto instead of bacon for a more delicate flavor.</li>\n</ul>\n"
