        "content": "<p><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Advanced</p>\n<p><strong>Servings:</strong> 6-8</p>\n<h3>Time Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Prep Time:</strong> 15 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Wet-Aging Time:</strong> 3-7 days (refrigerated, vacuum sealed)</li>\n  <li><strong>Cook Time:</strong> 3 hours slow roast + 30 minutes crispy finish</li>\n  <li><strong>Total Time:</strong> 4-7 days (including aging)</li>\n  <li><strong>Storage Duration:</strong> Frozen 18-24 months, Refrigerated aged 7 days</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why This Meal is Special</h3>\n<p>Wet-aging pork belly in a vacuum-sealed bag with Chinese five-spice creates an incredibly tender, restaurant-quality result. The vacuum environment allows enzymes to break down tough collagen while preventing oxidation. After aging, the pork crisps perfectly with a lacquered skin and melt-in-mouth fat layersâ€”impossible to achieve without the vacuum aging step.</p>\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\n<h4>For the Dry Rub:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>1.5 kg pork belly, skin-on (3.3 lbs)</li>\n  <li>3 tbsp Chinese five-spice powder (45g)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp brown sugar (30g / 1 oz)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp salt (15g)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp white pepper (5g)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp garlic powder (5g)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp ginger powder (5g)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>For the Glaze:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>3 tbsp soy sauce (45ml)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp honey (30ml)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp rice vinegar (15ml)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp sesame oil (15ml)</li>\n  <li>2 cloves garlic, minced (10g / 0.35 oz)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Equipment</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer</li>\n  <li>Large vacuum sealer bags</li>\n  <li>Roasting pan with rack</li>\n  <li>Sharp knife (for scoring)</li>\n  <li>Meat thermometer</li>\n  <li>Brush for glazing</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Instructions</h3>\n<h4>Preparation & Aging:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Score the pork belly skin in a crosshatch pattern, cutting through skin but not into meat (1cm/0.4 inch apart).</li>\n  <li>Combine all dry rub ingredients in a bowl.</li>\n  <li>Rub the spice mixture all over the pork belly, massaging into the scored skin and meat surfaces.</li>\n  <li>Place pork belly into a large vacuum sealer bag.</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal on <strong>normal setting</strong> (pork belly is firm enough to handle pressure).</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Wet-Aging Process:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Refrigerate for <strong>minimum 3 days, optimal 7 days</strong> at 1-4Â°C (34-39Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Flip the bag daily to ensure even aging.</li>\n  <li><strong>Food Science:</strong> During this time, natural enzymes break down connective tissue while the vacuum prevents spoilage. The five-spice aroma infuses through all fat layers.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Slow Roast (Day of Cooking):</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Remove pork from vacuum bag. Pat skin completely dry with paper towels (critical for crispy skin).</li>\n  <li>Let sit at room temperature for 30 minutes.</li>\n  <li>Preheat oven to 160Â°C (320Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Place pork belly skin-side up on a roasting rack.</li>\n  <li>Slow roast for 2.5-3 hours until meat is fork-tender (internal temp 88Â°C / 190Â°F).</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Crispy Finish:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Increase oven temperature to 220Â°C (425Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Combine glaze ingredients and brush over the meat (not the skin).</li>\n  <li>Roast for 25-30 minutes until skin is deeply browned and crackling.</li>\n  <li>Watch carefully to prevent burning.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Serving:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Rest for 10 minutes, then slice into thick strips.</li>\n  <li>Serve immediately while skin is crispy.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Storage</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (raw, vacuum sealed):</strong> 18-24 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (wet-aging):</strong> 7 days maximum</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (cooked):</strong> 5 days</li>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (cooked, vacuum sealed):</strong> 6-8 months</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Pro Tips</h3>\n<h4>Vacuum Advantage:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Wet-aging in vacuum creates enzyme activity without oxygen = tender meat, no spoilage.</li>\n  <li>The five-spice deeply penetrates all fat layers, creating consistent flavor throughout.</li>\n  <li>You can age for up to 7 days safely (impossible without vacuum sealing).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Cooking Tips:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Critical:</strong> Skin must be bone dry before final roasting for crackling to form.</li>\n  <li>If skin isn't crisping, increase heat to 240Â°C (465Â°F) and watch closely.</li>\n  <li>Don't skip the slow roastâ€”this is what makes the fat tender and gelatinous.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Serving Suggestions:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Slice into strips and serve with steamed buns (gua bao).</li>\n  <li>Dice and add to fried rice or ramen.</li>\n  <li>Serve with pickled vegetables to cut the richness.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Variations:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Korean Version:</strong> Use gochugaru (chili flakes) + gochujang in the glaze.</li>\n  <li><strong>Thai Version:</strong> Add lemongrass and galangal to the rub.</li>\n</ul>\n"
