        "content": "<p><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Easy</p>\n<p><strong>Servings:</strong> 8-10 (yields 1.2kg / 2.6 lbs pulled meat)</p>\n<h3>Time Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Prep Time:</strong> 15 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Marination Time:</strong> 30 minutes (vacuum) or overnight (traditional)</li>\n  <li><strong>Cook Time:</strong> 3-4 hours slow cook</li>\n  <li><strong>Total Time:</strong> 4 hours</li>\n  <li><strong>Storage Duration:</strong> Frozen 12-18 months per portion</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why This Meal is Special</h3>\n<p>Vacuum-sealing carnitas portions with their cooking juices creates self-basting meal packs. When reheated, the sealed environment steams the meat in its own fat, recreating the juicy texture of fresh carnitas. Pre-portioning means you can pull one bag for tacos, another for burritos, without thawing the entire batch.</p>\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\n<h4>For the Pork:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>2 kg boneless pork shoulder, cut into 5cm chunks (4.4 lbs)</li>\n  <li>1 orange, juiced (80ml / 1/3 cup)</li>\n  <li>2 limes, juiced (60ml / 1/4 cup)</li>\n  <li>6 cloves garlic, minced (30g / 1 oz)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp ground cumin (30g)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp dried oregano (15g)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp salt (15g)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp black pepper (5g)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp chipotle powder (5g) - optional for heat</li>\n  <li>2 bay leaves</li>\n  <li>250ml water or chicken stock (1 cup)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Equipment</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer</li>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer bags (quart or gallon size)</li>\n  <li>Large pot or Dutch oven (or slow cooker)</li>\n  <li>Two forks for shredding</li>\n  <li>Slotted spoon</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Instructions</h3>\n<h4>Marination:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>In a large bowl, combine orange juice, lime juice, minced garlic, cumin, oregano, salt, pepper, and chipotle powder.</li>\n  <li>Add pork chunks and toss to coat evenly.</li>\n  <li>Transfer pork and marinade to a vacuum sealer bag (or divide between 2 bags if needed).</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal on <strong>gentle setting</strong> (pulse mode recommended).</li>\n  <li>Marinate for 30 minutes minimum (or refrigerate overnight for deeper flavor).</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Cooking:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Heat a large pot or Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Add a splash of oil.</li>\n  <li>Remove pork from vacuum bag (reserve marinade).</li>\n  <li>Brown pork chunks in batches, 2-3 minutes per side.</li>\n  <li>Return all pork to pot. Add reserved marinade, bay leaves, and water/stock.</li>\n  <li>Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low. Cover and simmer for 3-4 hours until pork is fall-apart tender.</li>\n  <li><strong>Alternative:</strong> Cook in slow cooker on LOW for 6-8 hours.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Shredding & Crisping:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Remove pork chunks with a slotted spoon. Discard bay leaves.</li>\n  <li>Shred pork with two forks. Return to pot and toss in cooking liquid to keep moist.</li>\n  <li><strong>Optional Crispy Step:</strong> Spread shredded pork on a baking sheet. Broil for 3-5 minutes until edges crisp, watching carefully.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Portioning for Freezer:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Let carnitas cool to room temperature (30-45 minutes).</li>\n  <li>Divide into meal-sized portions (300-400g / 10-14 oz each serves 2-3 tacos).</li>\n  <li>Add 2-3 tablespoons of cooking liquid to each portion.</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal each portion on <strong>gentle setting</strong>.</li>\n  <li>Freeze flat for easy storage.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Storage</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (vacuum sealed portions):</strong> 12-18 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (cooked):</strong> 5-7 days</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (marinated raw):</strong> 2-3 days</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Pro Tips</h3>\n<h4>Vacuum Advantage:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Marination in 30 minutes vs. overnight with traditional method.</li>\n  <li>Cooking liquid sealed with meat creates self-basting packsâ€”no dry reheated carnitas.</li>\n  <li>Individual portions mean you use only what you need.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Reheating from Frozen:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Microwave:</strong> Cut corner of sealed bag, microwave on HIGH for 3-4 minutes, stirring halfway.</li>\n  <li><strong>Skillet:</strong> Thaw in fridge overnight, then reheat in skillet over medium heat until crispy.</li>\n  <li><strong>Oven:</strong> Thaw, spread on baking sheet, heat at 180Â°C (350Â°F) for 15 minutes.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Serving Suggestions:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Tacos with diced onion, cilantro, and lime</li>\n  <li>Burrito bowls with rice, beans, and guacamole</li>\n  <li>Nachos topping</li>\n  <li>Quesadillas</li>\n  <li>On top of loaded fries</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Variations:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Coca-Cola Carnitas:</strong> Add 200ml Coke to cooking liquid for caramelized sweetness.</li>\n  <li><strong>Spicy Version:</strong> Double the chipotle and add jalapeÃ±os to cooking liquid.</li>\n</ul>\n"
