        "content": "<p><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Medium</p>\n<p><strong>Servings:</strong> 6</p>\n<h3>Time Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Prep Time:</strong> 15 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Marination Time:</strong> 45 minutes (vacuum) or 12 hours (traditional)</li>\n  <li><strong>Cook Time:</strong> 30-35 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Total Time:</strong> 90 minutes (with vacuum marination)</li>\n  <li><strong>Storage Duration:</strong> Frozen 12-18 months, Refrigerated marinated 3 days</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why This Meal is Special</h3>\n<p>Vacuum sealing forces the sweet-savory char siu marinade deep into pork shoulder, creating the distinctive red-glazed exterior and juicy interior in under an hour. Traditional recipes require overnight marinating; vacuum pressure achieves the same penetration in 45 minutes. The sealed environment also prevents the honey from oxidizing, keeping the bright red color intact.</p>\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\n<h4>For the Marinade:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>1 kg pork shoulder (butt), cut into long strips 5cm thick (2.2 lbs)</li>\n  <li>4 tbsp hoisin sauce (60ml)</li>\n  <li>3 tbsp soy sauce (45ml)</li>\n  <li>3 tbsp honey (45ml)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp Shaoxing wine or dry sherry (30ml)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp brown sugar (30g / 1 oz)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp oyster sauce (15ml)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp Chinese five-spice powder (5g)</li>\n  <li>1/2 tsp white pepper (2.5g)</li>\n  <li>3 cloves garlic, minced (15g / 0.5 oz)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp ginger, grated (15g / 0.5 oz)</li>\n  <li>1/2 tsp red food coloring (optional, for traditional color)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>For Glazing:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>2 tbsp honey (30ml)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp marinade (reserved)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Equipment</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer</li>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer bags (gallon size)</li>\n  <li>Baking sheet with wire rack</li>\n  <li>Aluminum foil</li>\n  <li>Brush for glazing</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Instructions</h3>\n<h4>Preparation:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Cut pork shoulder into long strips approximately 5cm x 5cm x 15cm (2\" x 2\" x 6\").</li>\n  <li>In a bowl, whisk together hoisin, soy sauce, honey, Shaoxing wine, brown sugar, oyster sauce, five-spice, white pepper, garlic, ginger, and food coloring (if using).</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Vacuum Marination:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Place pork strips into a vacuum sealer bag.</li>\n  <li>Pour marinade over pork, ensuring all pieces are coated.</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal on <strong>gentle setting</strong> (pulse mode).</li>\n  <li>Massage the bag gently to distribute marinade evenly.</li>\n  <li>Refrigerate for <strong>45 minutes minimum</strong>. The vacuum will force the sugars and aromatics into the meat.</li>\n  <li><strong>Reserve 2 tablespoons of marinade</strong> before discarding the bag (for glazing).</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Roasting:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Preheat oven to 200Â°C (400Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Line a baking sheet with aluminum foil. Place a wire rack on top.</li>\n  <li>Remove pork from vacuum bag, letting excess marinade drip off.</li>\n  <li>Arrange pork strips on the wire rack, leaving space between each piece.</li>\n  <li>Roast for 15 minutes.</li>\n  <li>Flip pork strips, brush with honey-marinade glaze.</li>\n  <li>Roast for another 10 minutes.</li>\n  <li>Flip again, brush with more glaze, and roast for final 5-7 minutes until caramelized and slightly charred at edges.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Finishing:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Let rest for 5 minutes.</li>\n  <li>Slice against the grain into 1cm (0.4 inch) thick slices.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>For Freezing:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Cool cooked char siu completely.</li>\n  <li>Slice and portion into serving sizes.</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal portions (no additional liquid needed).</li>\n  <li>Freeze flat.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Storage</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (raw marinated):</strong> 3-4 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (cooked, sliced, vacuum sealed):</strong> 12-18 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (marinated raw):</strong> 3 days</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (cooked):</strong> 5-6 days</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Pro Tips</h3>\n<h4>Vacuum Advantage:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>45-minute marination vs. 12-24 hours traditional method.</li>\n  <li>Sugar penetrates deep into meat, creating caramelization throughout (not just on surface).</li>\n  <li>Vacuum prevents honey oxidation, keeping bright color and fresh flavor.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Cooking Tips:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Don't skip the wire rackâ€”you need air circulation for caramelization on all sides.</li>\n  <li>Watch closely during final minutes; honey can burn quickly.</li>\n  <li>For deeper char, broil for 1-2 minutes at the end (watch constantly).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Reheating from Frozen:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Thaw in refrigerator overnight.</li>\n  <li>Reheat in skillet over medium heat for 2-3 minutes per side.</li>\n  <li>Or microwave on MEDIUM for 1-2 minutes (less idealâ€”loses some crispness).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Serving Suggestions:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Over steamed rice with stir-fried vegetables</li>\n  <li>In ramen or wonton noodle soup</li>\n  <li>Fried rice mix-in</li>\n  <li>Steamed buns (char siu bao filling)</li>\n  <li>Cold sliced in Asian salads</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Variations:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Honey-Garlic Version:</strong> Double the honey and garlic, reduce hoisin.</li>\n  <li><strong>Spicy Version:</strong> Add 1-2 tsp chili bean paste (doubanjiang).</li>\n</ul>\n"
