        "content": "<p><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Medium</p>\n<p><strong>Servings:</strong> 4-6</p>\n<h3>Time Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Prep Time:</strong> 20 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Marination Time:</strong> 1 hour (vacuum) or 8 hours (traditional)</li>\n  <li><strong>Cook Time:</strong> 2.5-3 hours slow cook + 10 minutes broil</li>\n  <li><strong>Total Time:</strong> 4 hours</li>\n  <li><strong>Storage Duration:</strong> Frozen 18-24 months</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why This Meal is Special</h3>\n<p>Vacuum sealing gochujang marinade into pork ribs breaks down tough connective tissue while infusing the sweet-spicy Korean flavor deep into the bone. The low-pressure environment accelerates enzymatic tenderization, cutting marination time by 75%. After slow cooking and vacuum sealing, these ribs can be frozen for nearly 2 years and still taste freshly made when reheated.</p>\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\n<h4>For the Ribs:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>1.5 kg pork spare ribs (St. Louis style or baby back) (3.3 lbs)</li>\n  <li>4 tbsp gochujang (Korean chili paste) (60g / 2 oz)</li>\n  <li>3 tbsp soy sauce (45ml)</li>\n  <li>3 tbsp honey (45ml)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp rice vinegar (30ml)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp sesame oil (30ml)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp brown sugar (30g / 1 oz)</li>\n  <li>4 cloves garlic, minced (20g / 0.7 oz)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp ginger, grated (15g / 0.5 oz)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp black pepper (5g)</li>\n  <li>2 spring onions, chopped (20g / 0.7 oz)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp sesame seeds (for garnish)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Equipment</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer</li>\n  <li>Large vacuum sealer bags</li>\n  <li>Roasting pan or baking dish</li>\n  <li>Aluminum foil</li>\n  <li>Brush for glazing</li>\n  <li>Tongs</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Instructions</h3>\n<h4>Preparation:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Remove membrane from back of ribs (slide knife under membrane, grip with paper towel, and pull off).</li>\n  <li>Cut ribs into individual bones or 3-4 bone sections.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Marinade:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>In a bowl, whisk together gochujang, soy sauce, honey, rice vinegar, sesame oil, brown sugar, garlic, ginger, and black pepper until smooth.</li>\n  <li>Reserve 3 tablespoons of marinade for glazing.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Vacuum Marination:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Place ribs into a large vacuum sealer bag (or divide between 2 bags).</li>\n  <li>Pour marinade over ribs, ensuring all pieces are coated.</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal on <strong>gentle setting</strong> (pulse mode).</li>\n  <li>Massage bag to distribute marinade evenly.</li>\n  <li>Refrigerate for <strong>1 hour minimum</strong>. The vacuum pressure will force the marinade between the bones and into the meat.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Slow Cooking:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Preheat oven to 150Â°C (300Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Line a roasting pan with aluminum foil.</li>\n  <li>Remove ribs from vacuum bag, placing them in the pan bone-side down. Pour any excess marinade over top.</li>\n  <li>Cover tightly with aluminum foil.</li>\n  <li>Slow roast for 2.5-3 hours until meat is fall-off-the-bone tender.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Glazing & Caramelizing:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Remove foil. Increase oven temperature to 220Â°C (425Â°F) or turn on broiler.</li>\n  <li>Brush ribs with reserved marinade + honey mixture.</li>\n  <li>Broil for 8-10 minutes until glaze caramelizes and edges char slightly. Watch carefully to prevent burning.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Finishing:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Garnish with chopped spring onions and sesame seeds.</li>\n  <li>Serve immediately.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>For Freezing:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Cool cooked ribs completely.</li>\n  <li>Portion into serving sizes (3-4 bones per bag).</li>\n  <li>Add 2 tablespoons of cooking juices to each bag.</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal on <strong>gentle setting</strong>.</li>\n  <li>Freeze flat.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Storage</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (raw marinated):</strong> 4-6 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (cooked, vacuum sealed):</strong> 18-24 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (marinated raw):</strong> 2-3 days</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (cooked):</strong> 5-7 days</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Pro Tips</h3>\n<h4>Vacuum Advantage:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Marination in 1 hour vs. overnightâ€”gochujang penetrates deep into the meat.</li>\n  <li>The pressure helps break down collagen around the bones, making them extra tender.</li>\n  <li>Cooked ribs sealed with juices reheat perfectly with zero dryness.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Cooking Tips:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Low and slow is KEYâ€”don't rush the 2.5 hour cook time.</li>\n  <li>If ribs aren't tender after 2.5 hours, continue cooking and check every 15 minutes.</li>\n  <li>For smokier flavor, add 1 tsp liquid smoke to the marinade.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Reheating from Frozen:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Thaw in refrigerator overnight.</li>\n  <li><strong>Oven:</strong> Heat at 180Â°C (350Â°F) for 15-20 minutes, covered, then uncover and broil for 3 minutes.</li>\n  <li><strong>Microwave:</strong> Heat on MEDIUM for 3-4 minutes, then broil in oven for crispy finish.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Serving Suggestions:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>With kimchi fried rice</li>\n  <li>Steamed white rice and pickled radish</li>\n  <li>Korean lettuce wraps (ssam)</li>\n  <li>As a topping for bibimbap</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Variations:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Sweet Version:</strong> Increase honey to 5 tbsp and reduce gochujang to 2 tbsp.</li>\n  <li><strong>Extra Spicy:</strong> Add 1-2 tsp gochugaru (Korean chili flakes).</li>\n  <li><strong>Citrus Version:</strong> Add 2 tbsp orange juice to marinade for brightness.</li>\n</ul>\n"
