        "image": "ðŸ¥“",
        "description": "Vacuum sealing maple-mustard marinade into pork chops in just 20 minutes creates the same deep caramelization that typically requires hours of brining. The low-pressure environment forces the marinade into muscle fibers, preventing the dry, bland center that plagues quick-marinated chops. These freeze beautifully and can go from freezer to table in 30 minutes.",
        "prepTime": "10 minutes",
        "cookTime": "12-15 minutes",
        "totalTime": "45 minutes",
        "content": "<p><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Easy</p>\n<p><strong>Servings:</strong> 4</p>\n<h3>Time Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Prep Time:</strong> 10 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Marination Time:</strong> 20 minutes (vacuum) or 4 hours (traditional)</li>\n  <li><strong>Cook Time:</strong> 12-15 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Total Time:</strong> 45 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Storage Duration:</strong> Frozen 12-18 months, Refrigerated marinated 3 days</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why This Meal is Special</h3>\n<p>Vacuum sealing maple-mustard marinade into pork chops in just 20 minutes creates the same deep caramelization that typically requires hours of brining. The low-pressure environment forces the marinade into muscle fibers, preventing the dry, bland center that plagues quick-marinated chops. These freeze beautifully and can go from freezer to table in 30 minutes.</p>\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\n<h4>For the Marinade:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>4 bone-in pork chops, 2.5cm thick (1 inch) (800g / 1.75 lbs total)</li>\n  <li>4 tbsp pure maple syrup (60ml)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp Dijon mustard (30ml)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp soy sauce (30ml)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp olive oil (15ml)</li>\n  <li>2 cloves garlic, minced (10g / 0.35 oz)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp fresh thyme, chopped (or 1/2 tsp dried) (2g)</li>\n  <li>1/2 tsp black pepper (2.5g)</li>\n  <li>1/4 tsp salt (1.25g)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>For Searing:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>1 tbsp butter (15g)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp vegetable oil (15ml)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Equipment</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer</li>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer bags (gallon size)</li>\n  <li>Cast iron skillet or heavy pan</li>\n  <li>Meat thermometer</li>\n  <li>Tongs</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Instructions</h3>\n<h4>Preparation:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Pat pork chops dry with paper towels.</li>\n  <li>If chops have thick fat cap, score it in 3-4 places (prevents curling).</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Marinade:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>In a bowl, whisk together maple syrup, Dijon mustard, soy sauce, olive oil, garlic, thyme, pepper, and salt.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Vacuum Marination:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Place pork chops into a vacuum sealer bag in a single layer (use 2 bags if needed).</li>\n  <li>Pour marinade over chops, ensuring even coating.</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal on <strong>gentle setting</strong> (pulse mode to prevent liquid extraction).</li>\n  <li>Refrigerate for <strong>20 minutes minimum</strong>. The vacuum will force the marinade into the meat, creating juiciness throughout.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Cooking:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Remove chops from bag, letting excess marinade drip off (reserve marinade).</li>\n  <li>Pat chops dry with paper towel (for better sear).</li>\n  <li>Let sit at room temperature for 10 minutes.</li>\n  <li>Heat cast iron skillet over medium-high heat. Add butter and vegetable oil.</li>\n  <li>Once butter foams, add pork chops. Sear for 4-5 minutes without moving.</li>\n  <li>Flip and sear other side for 4-5 minutes until internal temperature reaches 63Â°C (145Â°F).</li>\n  <li>In final minute, spoon reserved marinade over chops (it will caramelize in the hot pan).</li>\n  <li>Remove from heat and rest for 5 minutes.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>For Freezing (Raw Marinated):</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>After marination, freeze chops in the sealed bag.</li>\n  <li>To cook from frozen: Thaw in refrigerator 12-24 hours, then follow cooking instructions above.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Storage</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (raw marinated, vacuum sealed):</strong> 12-18 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (marinated raw):</strong> 3 days</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (cooked):</strong> 4-5 days</li>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (cooked):</strong> 6-8 months (texture slightly degraded)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Pro Tips</h3>\n<h4>Vacuum Advantage:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>20-minute marination achieves the same depth as 4-hour traditional soak.</li>\n  <li>Maple syrup penetrates the meat (not just coating), creating caramelization from within.</li>\n  <li>No dry, bland centerâ€”every bite is evenly flavored and juicy.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Cooking Tips:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Don't overcook!</strong> Pork is safe at 63Â°C (145Â°F) with slight pink. It will reach 65Â°C during rest.</li>\n  <li>For perfect sear, make sure pan is HOT and chops are DRY before adding.</li>\n  <li>If chops are browning too fast, reduce heat to medium.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Serving Suggestions:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Mashed sweet potatoes and green beans</li>\n  <li>Apple slaw and roasted Brussels sprouts</li>\n  <li>Garlic butter pasta</li>\n  <li>Quinoa and roasted root vegetables</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Variations:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Apple-Maple:</strong> Add 2 tbsp apple cider vinegar to marinade, serve with sautÃ©ed apples.</li>\n  <li><strong>Spicy-Maple:</strong> Add 1 tsp chipotle powder or 1 tbsp hot sauce.</li>\n  <li><strong>Balsamic-Maple:</strong> Replace soy sauce with balsamic vinegar.</li>\n</ul>\n"
