        "id": "p-008",
        "name": "Italian Porchetta Roast",
        "category": "pork",
        "type": "premium",
        "isPremium": true,
        "image": "ðŸ–",
        "description": "Vacuum-sealing porchetta after dry brining and before wet-aging creates an intensely flavored, melt-in-mouth roast that rivals Italian delis. The vacuum environment allows the herb paste to penetrate deep into the rolled pork belly while collagen breaks down during aging. This is the ultimate make-ahead feastâ€”prep a week early, vacuum seal, age in the fridge, then roast for a showstopper meal.",
        "prepTime": "30 minutes",
        "cookTime": "3-4 hours",
        "totalTime": "1-7 days (depending on aging)",
        "content": "<p><strong>Difficulty:</strong> Advanced</p>\n<p><strong>Servings:</strong> 8-10</p>\n<h3>Time Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Prep Time:</strong> 30 minutes</li>\n  <li><strong>Dry Brining Time:</strong> 24 hours (refrigerated)</li>\n  <li><strong>Wet-Aging Time:</strong> 3-7 days (optional, for enhanced tenderness)</li>\n  <li><strong>Cook Time:</strong> 3-4 hours</li>\n  <li><strong>Total Time:</strong> 1-7 days (depending on aging)</li>\n  <li><strong>Storage Duration:</strong> Frozen raw 18-24 months, Cooked 12 months</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why This Meal is Special</h3>\n<p>Vacuum-sealing porchetta after dry brining and before wet-aging creates an intensely flavored, melt-in-mouth roast that rivals Italian delis. The vacuum environment allows the herb paste to penetrate deep into the rolled pork belly while collagen breaks down during aging. This is the ultimate make-ahead feastâ€”prep a week early, vacuum seal, age in the fridge, then roast for a showstopper meal.</p>\n<h3>Ingredients</h3>\n<h4>For the Pork:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>2.5 kg pork belly, boneless, skin-on (5.5 lbs)</li>\n  <li>500g pork loin, trimmed (1.1 lbs) - optional for leaner center</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp coarse sea salt (30g)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>For the Herb Paste:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>8 cloves garlic, minced (40g / 1.4 oz)</li>\n  <li>4 tbsp fresh rosemary, finely chopped (20g / 0.7 oz)</li>\n  <li>3 tbsp fresh sage, finely chopped (15g / 0.5 oz)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp fennel seeds, toasted and crushed (30g)</li>\n  <li>2 tbsp lemon zest (from 2 lemons) (12g)</li>\n  <li>1 tbsp black pepper, coarsely ground (15g)</li>\n  <li>1 tsp chili flakes (5g) - optional</li>\n  <li>60ml olive oil (1/4 cup)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Equipment</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li>Vacuum sealer</li>\n  <li>Large vacuum sealer bags</li>\n  <li>Sharp knife for scoring</li>\n  <li>Kitchen twine</li>\n  <li>Roasting pan with rack</li>\n  <li>Meat thermometer</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Instructions</h3>\n<h4>Day 1 - Preparation & Dry Brining:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Lay pork belly skin-side down on cutting board. Score the meat side in a crosshatch pattern (don't cut through).</li>\n  <li>If using pork loin, place it lengthwise in the center of the belly.</li>\n  <li>Sprinkle 2 tbsp coarse salt evenly over the meat side.</li>\n  <li>Wrap loosely in plastic wrap. Refrigerate for 24 hours (dry brine tenderizes and seasons).</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Day 2 - Herb Paste & Rolling:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Toast fennel seeds in a dry pan for 2 minutes until fragrant. Crush with mortar and pestle.</li>\n  <li>Combine crushed fennel, garlic, rosemary, sage, lemon zest, black pepper, chili flakes, and olive oil into a thick paste.</li>\n  <li>Remove pork from refrigerator. Pat meat side dry (leave skin dry too).</li>\n  <li>Spread herb paste evenly over the meat side, pressing into the score marks.</li>\n  <li>Roll the pork belly tightly from one short end to the other (like a Swiss roll), keeping skin on the outside.</li>\n  <li>Tie with kitchen twine at 3cm (1 inch) intervalsâ€”tie TIGHTLY to prevent unrolling.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Vacuum Wet-Aging (Optional but Recommended):</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Place rolled, tied porchetta into a large vacuum sealer bag.</li>\n  <li>Vacuum seal on <strong>normal setting</strong> (it's firm enough to handle pressure).</li>\n  <li>Refrigerate for <strong>3-7 days</strong> at 1-4Â°C (34-39Â°F).</li>\n  <li><strong>Food Science:</strong> Natural enzymes break down collagen, making the meat ultra-tender while vacuum prevents spoilage.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Day of Cooking:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Remove porchetta from vacuum bag 1 hour before cooking (bring to room temperature).</li>\n  <li>Pat skin completely DRY (critical for crackling).</li>\n  <li>Score the skin in parallel lines, 1cm (0.4 inch) apart, cutting through skin but not meat.</li>\n  <li>Rub skin with 1 tsp salt.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Roasting:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Preheat oven to 160Â°C (320Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Place porchetta on a roasting rack, skin-side up.</li>\n  <li>Slow roast for 3-3.5 hours until internal temperature reaches 88Â°C (190Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Increase oven to 240Â°C (465Â°F).</li>\n  <li>Roast for 20-30 minutes until skin crackles and turns golden brown. Watch closelyâ€”skin can burn quickly.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Resting & Serving:</h4>\n<ol>\n  <li>Rest for 15-20 minutes.</li>\n  <li>Remove twine. Slice into 1-2 cm thick rounds, ensuring each slice has crackling.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>For Freezing (Raw, Rolled):</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>After rolling and tying (step 10), vacuum seal and freeze for up to 18-24 months.</li>\n  <li>Thaw in refrigerator for 48 hours before cooking.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>For Freezing (Cooked):</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Cool completely, slice, and vacuum seal portions.</li>\n  <li>Reheat at 180Â°C (350Â°F) for 15-20 minutes (crackling won't be as crisp).</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Storage</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (raw rolled, vacuum sealed):</strong> 18-24 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (wet-aging):</strong> 7 days maximum</li>\n  <li><strong>Frozen (cooked):</strong> 12 months</li>\n  <li><strong>Refrigerated (cooked):</strong> 5-7 days</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Pro Tips</h3>\n<h4>Vacuum Advantage:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Wet-aging for 7 days creates collagen breakdown = fall-apart tender meat.</li>\n  <li>Herb paste penetrates 2-3cm deep (impossible without vacuum).</li>\n  <li>Freeze entire rolled roasts for future feastsâ€”thaw and cook anytime.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Cooking Tips:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Critical:</strong> Skin must be bone-dry for crackling. Pat multiple times.</li>\n  <li>If skin isn't crackling, increase heat to maximum and watch continuously.</li>\n  <li>Low and slow roasting is essential for tender meatâ€”don't rush it.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Serving Suggestions:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li>Serve in crusty Italian rolls with arugula and aioli</li>\n  <li>Slice thick and serve with roasted potatoes and fennel</li>\n  <li>Dice and add to pasta or risotto</li>\n  <li>Cold sliced in sandwiches</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Variations:</h4>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Spicy Version:</strong> Double chili flakes and add 2 tbsp harissa to herb paste.</li>\n  <li><strong>Tuscan Version:</strong> Add 2 tbsp sun-dried tomatoes (chopped) to herb paste.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>END OF TIER 2 PORK RECIPES</h4>\n<p><strong>Total Recipes Created:</strong> 8</p>\n<p><strong>Coverage:</strong> Premium, Standard, and Easy difficulty levels</p>\n<p><strong>Cuisine Diversity:</strong> Asian, Mexican, Korean, Greek, Italian</p>\n<p><strong>Storage Options:</strong> Raw marinated, cooked portioned, flash-frozen for convenience</p>\n"
